<subsection xml:id="subsec-Angles-in-a-parallelogram">
    <title>Angles in a parallelogram</title>

    <p>
        A parallelogram is a geometrical shape whose sides are parallel to each other. 
        It is a type of polygon having four sides (also called quadrilateral), where the pair of parallel sides are equal in length.
            The Sum of adjacent angles of a parallelogram is equal to 180 degrees
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <term>Properties of a parallelogram</term>
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The opposite sides of a parallelogram are equal in length. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The opposite angles are equal in measure.
                    <me>\angle p = \angle r</me>
                    <me>\angle q = \angle s</me>
                    
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Also, the interior angles on the same side of the transversal are supplementary.
                    <me>\angle p + \angle q = 180^\circ </me>
                    <me>\angle q + \angle r = 180^\circ </me>
                    <me>\angle r + \angle s = 180^\circ </me>
                    <me>\angle s + \angle p = 180^\circ </me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The Sum of all the interior angles equals <m>360^\circ</m> 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
       
    </p>

