    <example>

        <statement>
            <p>
                In the figure below, work out the sizes of angles marked <m>x</m>, <m>y</m> and <m>z</m>.
            </p>

            <image width="100%">
                <shortdescription>Parallelogram</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="parallelogram">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \usetikzlibrary{quotes,angles}
                        \draw(2,4) coordinate (D)-- (0,0) coordinate (A)-- (6,0) coordinate (B)--(8,4)coordinate(C)--(2,4)coordinate(D);
                        <!-- \node at (-0.2,0){A};
                        \node at (6.2,0){B};
                        \node at (8.2,4){C};
                        \node at (1.8,4){D}; -->
                        \pic["$z$", draw,-&gt;,black, angle radius=1cm] {angle=B--A--D};
                        \pic["$108$", draw,-&gt;,black, angle radius=1cm] {angle=A--D--C};
                        \pic["$x$", draw,-&gt;,black, angle radius=1cm] {angle=D--C--B};
                        \pic["$y$", draw,-&gt;,black, angle radius=1cm] {angle=C--B--A};

                        
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
                
        </statement>    

        <solution>
            <p>
                Angles marked <m>z</m> and <m>180^\circ</m> are co-interior angles.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore:
            </p>
            <p>
                Angle marked <m>z = 180^\circ </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x=72^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Angles marked <m>x</m> and <m>180^\circ</m> are co-interior angles.Therefore:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \text{Angle marked } x = 180^\circ-108^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x=72^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                    Angle marked <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are co-interior angles.Therefore:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x + y = 180^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    y = 180^\circ - x
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    y = 180^\circ - 72^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                        y = 108^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>

        </solution>

    </example>
